04472nam a22007335i 9789048521500DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485215007 a10.1515/97890485215002doi  a(DE-B1597)517613  a(OCoLC)751962319  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a305.81 aCoello, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSignificant difference? A comparative analysis of multicultural policies in the United Kingdom and the Netherlands /cLaura Coello; ed. by Joel Cahen, Ido de Haan, David J. Wertheim. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (64 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The choice in policies: Assimilation, Integration and Multiculturalism -- t2. Multiculturalism -- t3. Multiculturalism in practice -- t4. Conclusion: Did Multiculturalism fail? -- tBibliography -- tAppendices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aViolent incidents that took place in 2004 and 2005 in the Netherlands and the UK respectively prompted people to claim that multiculturalism had failed. This claim requires an assessment of the effect of the policies that were drafted based on this political philosophy. In this study, the author analyses two sets of policies developed from multiculturalism: policies of anti-discrimination of minorities and their labour market participation. The effect of these policies is assessed by studying the policy objectives and their results.Based on this review, the author concludes that while there is still much to achieve in the fields of anti-discrimination and labour market participation, multiculturalism did not fail in the UK. On the contrary, it created a positive public perception of diversity and a high participation of minorities in the labour market. This contrasts with results achieved in the Netherlands where policies have fluctuated in such a way that the public attitude towards diversity is ambivalent and the participation of minorities in the labour market is much lower than that of their native counterpart.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCahen, Joel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWertheim, David J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 ade Haan, Ido, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066278840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048521500zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048521500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048521500.jpg  a978-3-11-060651-5  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2002d2015  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK